u =  rac{{m{c^2}{\alpha ^2}(2n - 1)}}{{2h\;{n^2}{{(n - 1)}^2}}}{/tex} For large n, (2n - 1) = 2n, and (n - 1) = n {tex}
u =  rac{{m{c^2}{\alpha ^2} \cdot 2n}}{{2h\;{n^2} \cdot {n^2}}} =  rac{{m{c^2}{\alpha ^2}}}{{h\;{n^3}}}{/tex} Putting {tex}\alpha =  rac{{2\pi K{e^2}}}{{ch}}{/tex} we get, {tex}
u =  rac{{m{c^2}}}{{h\;{n^3}}} \cdot  rac{{4{\pi ^2}{K^2}{e^4}}}{{{c^2}{h^2}}}{/tex} {tex}
u =  rac{{4{\pi ^2}m{K^2}{e^4}}}{{{n^3}{h^3}}}{/tex} .....(i) In Bohr&#39;s atom model, velocity of electron in nth orbit is {tex}v =  rac{{n\;h}}{{2\pi mr}}{/tex} and radius of nth orbit is {tex}r =  rac{{{n^2}{h^2}}}{{4{\pi ^2}mK{e^2}}}( ecause Z = 1){/tex} Frequency of revolution of electron, {tex}
u =  rac{\upsilon }{{2\pi r}} =  rac{{nh}}{{2\pi mr}}\left( { rac{{4{\pi ^2}mK{e^2}}}{{2\pi .{n^2}{h^2}}}} ight){/tex} {tex}
u =  rac{{K{e^2}}}{{nh \cdot r}} =  rac{{K{e^2}}}{{nh}}\left( { rac{{4{\pi ^2}mK{e^2}}}{{{n^2}{h^2}}}} ight){/tex} {tex}
u =  rac{{4{\pi ^2}m{K^2}{e^4}}}{{{n^3}{h^3}}}{/tex} which is the same as (i) Hence for large values of n, classical frequency of revolution of electron in nth orbit is the same as the frequency of radiation emitted when hydrogen atom de-excites from level (n) to level (n - 1).

